pullRequest.body:
A linter that makes sure that, when multiple goals are present, they are enclosed in `·`s.

Adaptations (the order is chronological, there should be no dependency among them):
* #12338,
* #12361,
* #12372,
* #12560,
* #12834,
* #12381,
* #12908,
* #14939,

plus many many more that this comment is too small to contain.

I guess bors is case sensitive?

bors merge
Already running a review
Nope, just didn't add the label for some reason.
I had checked that `bors` was running, but did not notice the missing label...

I had noticed that the commits to master between when this PR was green and when it was approved looked like they would have not introduced some missing `·`, so I put the PR quickly on the queue from my phone: I know that `r+` has a tendency to be auto-corrected, but I did not think about capitalization of `bors`!

Pull request successfully merged into master.

  * [Lint style](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/11434521370/job/31808228872)
  * [Build](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/11434521370/job/31808229404)

Thank you for the changes (and sorry that I didn't find time to propose something myself). In particular, the new error message seems much clearer to me! I have some more comments on the comments. I think that is close to all I have to comment on this PR.

Thanks for writing this linter! The code is quite short, but I know that this always takes more thought than one might think. The linter does what it says and looks well-written. I have one high-level comment: intuitively, I would expect its logic to be slightly different (see below). 

I also reviewed everything else carefully: as you know by now, that entails some word-smithing suggestions and a number of minor comments. (I pushed some tweaks directly; feel free to revert or discuss anything you do not agree with.)
Michael, thank you very much for the comment!  I think that this is (finally) ready again for review!

Thank you for the changes (and sorry that I didn't find time to propose something myself). In particular, the new error message seems much clearer to me! I have some more comments on the comments. I think that is close to all I have to comment on this PR.
Michael, thank you for all your reviewing effort!
Suggestions on what to usefully say would be very welcome here!

This is a false positive of the linter: after `funext`, there is a single goal left.
Can you add a test for this?
Should this move to `ignoreBranch`? What about `try`?

This comment is hard to understand. Can you clarify what this is about?

Are these basically tactic combinators (then repeat' and try should go here instead)? What does "branch" in the name mean; can you elaborate?
I added a longer explanation.

Trying to articulate when the linter errors gave me an idea about how to phrase the error message.
- I could be nice to say "`by_cases 0 = 0` produced two goals", but that might be hard in general
- Something that *is* feasible is to change the wording of the error, something like
```
warning: there are 2 unclosed goals before 'exact .intro', and one stays unsolved
please focus on the current goal, for instance using `.` (typed as "\.")
I also updated the error message, thanks!

```suggestion
-- The linter ignores `conv`, `conv_lhs` and `conv_rhs`, but keeps linting afterwards.
Added this test, to clarify which lines warn, and to show that several warnings also work.

```suggestion
-- `assumption'` is allowed, as it is useful precisely when there are multiple active goals.
What do you think about "... is allowed as a proof scoping tactic"?
Is this item still current? My understanding is that nobody complained much about this.

```suggestion
## TODO

Re-re-thinking this wording, I am not completely happy: tactics creating side goals are fine. The point is when there are multiple active goals, but a tactic only acts on one of them. What do you think about something like the following?

```
The "multiGoal" linter emits a warning when there is more than a single goal in scope, but a tactic only acts on one of them.

As mandated by the mathlib style guide, when new goals arise as side conditions or steps,
they should be focused. It is common for tactics to split one goal into several steps, or to leave side conditions to be checked. In these cases, goals should be focused until there is only one active goal at a time. Typically, this focusing is achieved by the `cdot`: `·`, but, the `focus` or `on_goal` tactics (for example) serve a similar purpose.

The only exception to this rule are tactic combinators like `all_goals`, intended to run one or several tactics on several goals at once.
```

I am in fact not fully sure if the first sentence is correct: would the following situation error?
-- one goal before
tactic1 -- two goals now
tactic2 -- closes both

In any case, can you add a test for something like this? My last adaptation PR contained one.

You are right: there is an extra exception which is a tactic that starts with more than one open goals and the tactic closes *all* goals.  I.e., the linter shuts up if no goals are left.  I added this to the description.

Thanks, this definitely helps! Do you have the energy to add a test for such a situation? (Would that be interesting? My motivation is to ensure these edge cases are not changed accidentally, and adding a test is an easy way to do so. Mathlib proofs change over time.)

I added such a test: I am not sure that it is interesting, nor necessarily a behaviour that should be enforced.  In any case, mathlib certainly exploits this already somewhere, so a change in this case would be noticed anyway!
Thinking closer: I think it's clearer to delete this sentence, and move tactic combinators to the next list.

The two lists are not interchangeable, as they serve different purposes (although some tactics could be in either list, since they may be, e.g. finishing tactics, so they are guaranteed to not leave a side goal.

`exclusions` are tactics that can be used when more than one goal is active and the linter will not complain.  The typical example is the focusing dot `·`, which is "the" escape from a multi-goal situation.

`ignoreBranch` are tactics that work like a `set_option linter.multiGoal false in [whatever follows of the proof]`. The typical example is `conv`, where internal goal management makes the linter confused and it does not report accurately the goal status.
Thank you; this helps!

In terms of style, what do you think about this rephrasing?
`getManyGoals t` returns the syntax nodes in `t` corresponding to tactic calls which
- leave at least one goal that was not present before it ran
- are not excluded through `exclusions` or `ignoreBranch`

(This needs to be adapted if `ignoreBranch` is renamed or the logic tweaked, as indicated below.)
I used your version, thanks!
Does `(args.map getManyGoals).flatten` also work? This is what the `refine'` linter uses.
Almost: this is a persistent array, so there is an extra `toArray` that I inserted.
Can you comment this branch? Why do you need it?

As you wrote via DM, this uses a heuristic: you use the heuristic "meta-variables have the same name" to determine whether a tactic only modifies a goal, or creates new ones. Can you add a comment to this effect?
Never mind, that comment applies to the flexible linter, but not this one.
Never mind, that comment applies to the flexible linter, but not this one.

This is my only high-level comment: I agree the code does what it says, but I wonder if this is what you or I want.

Intuitively, I would rather expect the linter to fire if "goalsBefore.length > 2 and goalsAfter.length != 0", which is slightly different. (This is the wording I proposed above.) What do you think?
Thank you; this is much clearer! I'm stumbling a bit over the term "proof branch" - I don't know a better term though. (Do you?)
Not really: I view proofs as (syntax) "trees" and this is a "branch" of the "tree"...
Should this sentence move after the "There is some overlap in scope between `ignoreBranch` and `exclusions`."? (Otherwise, what does "of both" refer to?)
Thanks, I swapped the sentences!
Very minor nit: move the "else" to the beginning of the next line? Up to you.
Moved!
Can you also mention what the returned natural number is, please?
Done!

A merge conflict, I guess:
```suggestion
Indeed, badly resolved!
Let's get this linter in before the Lean bump :-)
Not a native speaker, but: is "afterwards" better English?
I don't know, both sound correct to me, so I went with your version!

This is getting into copy-editing territory: this description covers everything - but re-reading this again (after a few months), I find this hard to parse. There are exceptions, and exceptions of exceptions... can the same content be said more clearly and directly? Something like:

```
Suppose there are multiple goals in scope, and the next tactic call does not close them all. (This is a common situation, as tactic can split one goal into several steps, or to leave side conditions to be checked.)

There are a few tactics (such as `skip`, `skip` or the `try` combinator) that are intended to work specifically in such a situation. Otherwise, the mathlib style guide ask that goals be be focused until there is only one active goal at a time.
If this focusing does not happen, the linter emits a warning.
Typically, the focusing is achieved by the `cdot`: `·`, but, e.g., `focus` or `on_goal x` also serve a similar purpose.
```

This is longer and less concise, but (I think) clearer: less complicated sentences, less negation
Included.
